https://cwcyau.github.io/authors/admin/ Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000 https://cwcyau.github.io/authors/admin/ <p>I am Professor of Artificial Intelligence at the <a href="http://www.ox.ac.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">University of Oxford</a> in a joint position between <a href="https://www.wrh.ox.ac.uk/team/christoper-yau" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Nuffield Department for Women's and Reproductive Health</a> and the <a href="https://www.npdh.ox.ac.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Nuffield Department of Population Health</a>. My group is based at the <a href="http://www.bdi.ox.ac.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Big Data Institute</a>. I am also Director of the <a href="https://www.hdruk.ac.uk/talent-training/hdr-uk-turing-phd-programme-funded-by-the-wellcome-trust/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Health Data Research-Alan Turing Institute Wellcome PhD programme in Health Data Science</a> and a recipient of the <a href="https://www.ukri.org/news/new-turing-ai-fellows-to-deliver-world-class-ai-research/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">UKRI Turing Artificial Intelligence Fellowship</a>.</p> <h2 id="about-me">About Me</h2> <p>I studied undergraduate Engineering at Cambridge where I did my masters dissertation with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Blake_%28scientist%29" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Professor Andrew Blake</a> at Microsoft Research on digital image analysis. Afterwards, I joined the EPSRC-funded Life Sciences Interface Doctoral Training Centre, led by <a href="https://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/people/david.gavaghan/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Professor David Gavaghan</a> in Oxford where I completed my doctoral thesis in Statistics under the supervision of <a href="http://www.stats.ox.ac.uk/~cholmes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Professor Chris Holmes</a>.</p> <p>I subsequently took up <a href="https://gtr.ukri.org/projects?ref=G0701810" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MRC Fellowship in Biomedical Informatics</a> before joining <a href="http://www.ic.ac.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Imperial College London</a> as a Lecturer in Statistics in the Department of Mathematics. I rejoined Oxford where I became Associate Professor in Genomic Medicine as a Principal Investigator at the <a href="http://www.well.ox.ac.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Wellcome Trust Centre for Human Genetics</a>. I then became Reader and then Professor of Artificial Intelligence at the <a href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">University of Birmingham</a> and the <a href="http://www.manchester.ac.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">University of Manchester</a> before returning to Oxford.</p> <p>I am a member of the <a href="https://mrc.ukri.org/funding/science-areas/methodology-research/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MRC Better Methods, Better Research</a> Programme Panel (formerly the Methodology Research Panel) and the <a href="https://mrc.ukri.org/successes/awards-recognition/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Millenium Medal</a> committee. I lead the Genomics England Clinical Interpretation Partnership in <a href="https://www.genomicsengland.co.uk/portfolio/quantitative-methods-machine-learning-and-functional-genomics-gecip-domain-various-universities/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Quantitative Methods, Functional Genomics and Machine Learning</a>. I am also a consultant for <a href="https://www.kheironmed.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kheiron Medical Technologies</a>, the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/medicines-and-healthcare-products-regulatory-agency" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Medicines & Healthcare products Regulatory Agency</a> and <a href="https://singulabio.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Singula Bio</a>. I was previously on the Taskforce group for the <a href="https://acmedsci.ac.uk/grants-and-schemes/mentoring-and-other-schemes/FLIER" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Academy of Medical Science FLIER programme</a>.</p> <h2 id="research-interests">Research Interests</h2> <p>For many years, I have been interested in the development of novel statistical methods for solving a broad spectrum of biomedical problems from microscopy to genomics to mental health. Real problems inspired and underpin the methodological research I do and getting to grips with real scientific investigations and experiments grounds the research in reality.</p> <p>My approach is normally Bayesian using formal probabilistic methods. This gives methods a coherent development framework allowing for greater rigour in model evaluation.</p> <p>I believe in a multi-disciplinary approach which involves working with and training not only statistical and machine learning scientists but also those from a biomedical, social science or clinical background.</p>
